<h1 class="hero-h">AI agents for operations: <em>the 2026 playbook.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Operations runs on data cleanup, reporting, and documentation - all things agents do well. The right deployment frees the ops team to focus on the high-leverage strategic work no agent can do.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">Short version</div><p class="verdict-p">Start with reporting automation and data cleanup agents. Add vendor management and documentation agents next. Stack: Claude or ChatGPT Team plus workflow automation (Zapier/Make) plus your data tools. Budget $200-$1,500/mo. ROI usually positive within 30 days on time-saved alone.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Where AI agents earn their keep in operations</h2>
<p class="body">Operations work breaks into process, data, and reporting. Agents are excellent at the data and reporting; humans are essential for process design and the cross-functional politics.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Reporting automation.</strong> Pull data from analytics, CRM, finance, and product; build the weekly/monthly reports that ops normally spends 4-8 hours producing. Free the ops team for analysis instead of assembly.</li>
<li><strong>Data cleanup.</strong> De-duplicate CRM records, normalize company names, fill missing fields from public data. The kind of cleanup project ops never gets to because it takes too long manually.</li>
<li><strong>Vendor management.</strong> Track contracts, renewals, and SLA commitments; surface what is due and what is at risk. Removes the spreadsheet-driven vendor management most ops teams limp along with.</li>
<li><strong>Process documentation.</strong> Watch how work flows through the company and produce written process docs. Maintains the institutional knowledge ops teams typically have to write themselves.</li>
<li><strong>Compliance and audit prep.</strong> Collect evidence, track controls, and produce audit-ready documentation. Cuts audit prep from weeks to days.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">The ops-agent pattern: agents handle the data and the documents; humans handle the process design and the people. Get the human-in-the-loop step right and the team scales without hiring.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Recommended starting stack</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Claude or ChatGPT Team ($20-$30/seat)</strong> for reasoning and writing.</li>
<li><strong>Zapier or Make ($30-$200/mo)</strong> for the orchestration layer.</li>
<li><strong>Your data tools (CRM, BI, finance system)</strong> as data sources.</li>
<li><strong>A dedicated agent platform</strong> if you want a no-code agent builder (Lindy, Relay, similar).</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Ops-agent stacks for mid-market typically run $200 to $1,500 per month.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">The ROI math</h2>
<p class="body">Easiest measurement is time saved on recurring work. A weekly report that took 6 hours and now takes 30 minutes saves 5.5 hours a week - about $30K of analyst time per year for a single workflow. Stack a handful of those and the budget pays back fast.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What AI agents should not do for your operations team</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Make process decisions. Agents document and execute; humans design.</li>
<li>Touch financial data unsupervised. Verify before posting.</li>
<li>Make commitments to vendors. The relationship is human.</li>
<li>Run unmaintained. Agents drift; an owner reviews monthly.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Will AI agents replace our ops team?</div><div class="faq-a">Not the strategic roles. Agents take the data and reporting work off ops analysts so they can focus on process design and cross-functional projects. Teams typically stay the same size and ship more.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What should we automate first?</div><div class="faq-a">Whichever recurring report takes the most ops time. The first wins build credibility for everything else.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How do we keep data clean once agents touch it?</div><div class="faq-a">Versioned changes, an audit trail, and human approval before bulk writes. Agents are excellent at proposing changes; humans approve.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Do we need a 'RevOps' or 'BizOps' specialist?</div><div class="faq-a">Not for tooling. Agent workflows fit normal ops responsibilities. A specialist makes sense when complexity demands it, not because of AI.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much should we budget?</div><div class="faq-a">$200 to $1,500 per month for the stack, with the variance driven by team size and agent platform choice.</div></div>
</div></section>

